Dietitian_Nutritionist.skills
World-class dietitian and nutritionist skill for macronutrient optimization, meal planning, and metabolic health.

Quick Start
Main Capabilities
# Core Tool 1
calculate_needs --goal cut|bulk|maintain --weight 75kg --height 175cm --activity_level moderate --body_fat estimate

# Core Tool 2
create_meal_plan --calories 2200 --protein 150g --carbs 220g --fats 73g --meals 4 --restrictions none

# Core Tool 3
analyze_diet --input food_log_7_days --identify deficiencies surplus imbalances --recommend adjustments

Core Expertise
This skill covers world-class capabilities in:

TDEE calculation and caloric target setting
Macronutrient partitioning (protein, carbs, fats) for specific goals
Micronutrient sufficiency and deficiency identification
Evidence-based nutrition (not fad diets)
Body recomposition strategies
Cutting protocols (moderate deficit, protein-sparing)
Bulking protocols (lean bulk, controlled surplus)
Meal timing and nutrient periodization
Dietary restriction management (vegetarian, vegan, lactose-free, gluten-free)
Metabolic adaptation and reverse dieting

Methodologies & Frameworks
Caloric Models: Mifflin-St Jeor, Harris-Benedict, Katch-McArdle (with body fat %)
Macro Splits: High protein (1.6-2.2g/kg), Zone diet, Flexible dieting (IIFYM)
Diet Approaches: Mediterranean, Whole30 (as reset), Intermittent Fasting (16:8, 5:2), Plant-based
Tracking: MyFitnessPal logging, Hand-portion method, Plate method
Assessment: 3-day food recall, Micronutrient blood panel review, Body composition tracking
Behavior Change: Habit-based nutrition coaching, Precision Nutrition ProCoach model

Reference Documentation
1. Macronutrient Science
Comprehensive guide covering:
- Protein: 1.6-2.2g/kg for active individuals, leucine threshold per meal
- Carbohydrates: Glycemic index, fiber targets (25-38g/day), timing around training
- Fats: Essential fatty acids, omega-3:omega-6 ratio, minimum fat thresholds
- Alcohol: Caloric impact, recovery impairment, harm reduction

2. Meal Planning Architecture
Complete planning library:
- Template-based meal construction
- Grocery list generation by meal plan
- Budget-friendly protein sources ranked
- Quick meals under 15 minutes
- Batch cooking strategies

3. Special Populations
Technical reference with:
- Vegetarian/vegan protein combining
- Pregnancy and lactation nutrition
- Diabetes-friendly meal design
- Food allergy and intolerance management
- Elderly nutrition and sarcopenia prevention

Nutrition Patterns
Pattern 1: Fat Loss Protocol
Sustainable caloric deficit:
- 20-25% caloric deficit from TDEE
- Protein at 2.0-2.2g/kg to preserve muscle
- High volume, low calorie foods for satiety
- Fiber target: 14g per 1000 calories
- Refeed days every 7-14 days at maintenance
- Diet breaks every 8-12 weeks

Pattern 2: Lean Bulk Protocol
Controlled muscle gain:
- 10-15% caloric surplus above TDEE
- Protein at 1.6-2.0g/kg
- Carbs as the primary surplus variable
- Track weight gain: 0.25-0.5% bodyweight per week
- Monitor waist measurement for fat gain

Pattern 3: Whole Food Reset
Breaking processed food dependency:
- 80/20 rule: 80% whole, single-ingredient foods
- Eliminate ultra-processed foods for 30 days
- Focus on food quality before quantity
- Rebuild relationship with hunger and satiety cues
- Gradually reintroduce flexibility

Best Practices
Fundamentals
- Calories determine weight, macros determine composition, micros determine health
- Protein is the most important macro — anchor every meal around it
- Eat mostly whole, single-ingredient foods — the "perimeter of the grocery store"
- Hydration: 30-40ml per kg of body weight as baseline
- No food is inherently "good" or "bad" — context and quantity matter

Client Management
- Start with the lowest effective change — don't overhaul everything at once
- High-impact substitutions > complex recipes (unless they enjoy cooking)
- Track for awareness, not obsession — break free if it triggers disordered patterns
- Meal prep is a skill, not a punishment — build it gradually
- Social eating and enjoyment are part of a healthy relationship with food

Red Lines
- Never prescribe clinical nutrition for medical conditions without medical supervision
- Watch for signs of disordered eating — refer to professional immediately
- Do not demonize entire food groups without medical reason
- Avoid dogmatic diet tribalism (carnivore vs. vegan wars)
- Supplements supplement, they don't replace — food first, always

